  <brief_title>Improvement in Baroreflex Sensitivity in OSAS</brief_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Nagoya University</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>Nagoya University</source>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Individuals with obstructive sleep apnea syndrome (OSAS) are at high risk for cardiovascular
      morbidity and mortality. The effect of long-term nocturnal therapy with continuous positive
      airway pressure (CPAP) on daytime baroreflex sensitivity (BRS), a predictor of cardiac death,
      was investigated in OSAS patients.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
